{{distinguish | Lambda cube}}

In the system of [[Term logic|Aristotelian logic]], the '''logical cube''' is a [[diagram]] representing the different ways in which each of the eight [[proposition]]s of the [[Formal system|system]] is logically related ('opposed') to each of the others.<ref>Hans Reichenbach, 1952, "The Syllogism revised", <em>Philosophy of Science</em> 19(1), pp. 1-16.</ref>  The system is also useful in the analysis of [[Term logic|syllogistic logic]], serving to identify the allowed logical conversions from one type to another.<ref>Paul Dekker, 2015, "Not Only Barbara", <em>Journal of Logic, Language, and Information</em> 24(2), pp. 95-129.</ref>

